Question 1

  1. Arrival delay of two or more hours
head(flights)
filter(flights, arr_delay >= 120)
  1. Flew to Houston (IAH or HOU)
filter(flights, dest %in% c("IAH","HOU"))
  1. Were operated by United, America, or Delta
filter(flights, carrier %in% c("UA", "AA", "DL"))
  1. Departed in summer (July, August, September)
filter(flights, month %in% c(7,8,9))

filter(flights, arr_delay>120 & dep_delay<=0)
  1. Were delayed by at least an hour but made up over 30 minutes in flight
filter(flights, dep_delay>=60 & (dep_delay-arr_delay)>=30)
  1. Departed between midnight and 6am (inclusive)
filter(flights, dep_time==2400 | dep_time<=600)

Question 2

?between()

This function is written in the form between(x, left, right). In essense, this is the same as the inequality left<=x<=right. Lets use this function for challenge 4!

filter(flights, between(month, 7, 9))

Question 4

NA^0
NA | TRUE
FALSE & NA

WellNA represents an unknown value. It doesnt necessarily mean that theres NO value. Were not operating on empty space. Anyway, those three expressions above are all cases of the values are irrelevant.
NA^0 = NA^(n-n) = (NAn)/(NAn) = 1 By properties of OR operators, if one value is TRUE, than the whole thing is TRUE NO MATTER WHAT
By properties of AND operators, if one value is FALSE, then the whole thing is FALSE NO MATTER WHAT

NA*0

Nowthis one is tricky. 0 times anything is 0, no? Well, in the previous cases, the NA values was either cancelled out or completely disregarded. In other words, it never had an active role in the operation; it was never used. In this case, however, the NA value is still actively used in the operation. Because it is technically used, it will output NA. (Okay, listen, Im just spitballing here. I honestly dont know)

Question 6

Trig functions provided by R include the basics (sine, cosine, tangent):

z<-c(1,-1,0.5,2)
sin(z)
cos(z)
tan(z)

The inverses (arcsine, arccosine, arctangent):

asin(z)
acos(z)
atan(z)

For angles in pi, not radians (i.e.sinpi(x)=sin(pi*x))

sinpi(1/2)
cospi(2)
tanpi(1/4)
